you really believe 100%?

75
00:03:20,480 --> 00:03:21,300
Not yet.

76
00:03:21,300 --> 00:03:23,590
Maybe it'll prove out in time.

77
00:03:23,590 --> 00:03:27,780
19 out of 20 is a little
more, but for most people,

78
00:03:27,780 --> 00:03:31,620
for 79% of you,
that's not enough.

79
00:03:31,620 --> 00:03:36,110
The 90 out of 100,000
seems like good odds,

80
00:03:36,110 --> 00:03:37,900
and it's well tested.

81
00:03:37,900 --> 00:03:44,130
19 out of 20, if the next person
tested doesn't get better,

82
00:03:44,130 --> 00:03:46,570
now you back to 90%.

83
00:03:46,570 --> 00:03:48,650
So that doesn't seem
like quite enough.

84
00:03:48,650 --> 00:03:53,372
What if were 95 out
of 100 patients.

85
00:03:53,372 --> 00:03:54,580
We'll let you click in there.

86
00:03:54,580 --> 00:03:57,020
Change number 2 to 95
out of 100 and let's

87
00:03:57,020 --> 00:04:00,370
see what people would do.

88
00:04:00,370 --> 00:04:02,780
Oh, you're very
obliging, 95 out of 100--

89
00:04:02,780 --> 00:04:04,230
PROFESSOR 2: Now
it's about 50-50.

90
00:04:04,230 --> 00:04:05,527
PROFESSOR: About 50-50.

91
00:04:05,527 --> 00:04:06,735
PROFESSOR 2: Between 2 and 3.

92
00:04:06,735 --> 00:04:09,250

93
00:04:09,250 --> 00:04:10,750
PROFESSOR:
Realistically, of course,

94
00:04:10,750 --> 00:04:11,833
what would you want to do?

95
00:04:11,833 --> 00:04:14,240
You'd want to do a
little more research

96
00:04:14,240 --> 00:04:17,730
and find out what these trials
were, how good experiments you

97
00:04:17,730 --> 00:04:20,820
thought they were, what
people are thinking about it.

98
00:04:20,820 --> 00:04:23,290
But with just this data, that's
what people would choose.

99
00:04:23,290 --> 00:04:25,040
And would people would
choose differently.

100
00:04:25,040 --> 00:04:27,360
OK.

101
00:04:27,360 --> 00:04:29,810
PROFESSOR 2: Let's see.

102
00:04:29,810 --> 00:04:33,750
So now I'm going to give you
a toy problem that actually

103
00:04:33,750 --> 00:04:37,470
mirrors the same kind of effect
we saw on the last slide.

104
00:04:37,470 --> 00:04:44,100
So, suppose in this MIT mug,
I have dice of two types,

105
00:04:44,100 --> 00:04:47,710
4-sided and 20-sided.

106
00:04:47,710 --> 00:04:48,210
All right?

107
00:04:48,210 --> 00:04:50,760
So I'm going to
reach into the mug.

108
00:04:50,760 --> 00:04:53,380
I'm not going to look.

109
00:04:53,380 --> 00:04:55,880
Much.

110
00:04:55,880 --> 00:04:58,935
I'm going to randomly
pull out a die.

111
00:04:58,935 --> 00:04:59,810
I'm going to roll it.

112
00:04:59,810 --> 00:05:02,750

113
00:05:02,750 --> 00:05:05,200
All right, I got a 1.

114
00:05:05,200 --> 00:05:06,450
OK.

115
00:05:06,450 --> 00:05:07,270
I got a 1.

116
00:05:07,270 --> 00:05:13,190
Now, just based on this
information, which type of die

117
00:05:13,190 --> 00:05:14,480
do you think I randomly chose?

118
00:05:14,480 --> 00:05:17,340

119
00:05:17,340 --> 00:05:18,091
The 4-sided.

120
00:05:18,091 --> 00:05:19,840
Someone want to give
an explanation of why

121
00:05:19,840 --> 00:05:21,728
they think the 4-sided
is more likely?

122
00:05:21,728 --> 00:05:23,307
AUDIENCE: It's
greater probability.

123
00:05:23,307 --> 00:05:24,890
PROFESSOR 2: It's
greater probability.

124
00:05:24,890 --> 00:05:28,180
What's the probability of
getting a 1 on the 4-sided die?

125
00:05:28,180 --> 00:05:30,230
And what about a 20-sided sided?

126
00:05:30,230 --> 00:05:30,960
OK.

127
00:05:30,960 --> 00:05:35,300
So we see that it would
be more likely to roll a 1

128
00:05:35,300 --> 00:05:38,180
with a 4-sided die than
with a 20-sided die.

129
00:05:38,180 --> 00:05:43,570
So, suppose I tell you that
I really in this cup only

130
00:05:43,570 --> 00:05:46,820
have one die of each type.

131
00:05:46,820 --> 00:05:49,380
So does that change
your analysis

132
00:05:49,380 --> 00:05:50,820
of which die is most likely?

133
00:05:50,820 --> 00:05:52,680
Don't hit forward yet.

134
00:05:52,680 --> 00:05:54,120
PROFESSOR: I would think of it.

135
00:05:54,120 --> 00:05:56,450
My hands are staying.

136
00:05:56,450 --> 00:06:00,130
PROFESSOR 2: Or do you want to
stick with the same reasoning?

137
00:06:00,130 --> 00:06:00,850
All right.

138
00:06:00,850 --> 00:06:02,683
Let me show you what's
actually in this cup.

139
00:06:02,683 --> 00:06:09,002

140
00:06:09,002 --> 00:06:09,960
PROFESSOR: Ouch.

141
00:06:09,960 --> 00:06:12,630
PROFESSOR 2: Oh, you
can't see it yet.

142
00:06:12,630 --> 00:06:15,720
Let's go with the
document camera.

143
00:06:15,720 --> 00:06:18,940

144
00:06:18,940 --> 00:06:22,610
OK, that was actually
what I had in this cup.

145
00:06:22,610 --> 00:06:24,560
Now what?

146
00:06:24,560 --> 00:06:27,200
So does this change at
all of your analysis

147
00:06:27,200 --> 00:06:29,250
which die you think I
rolled and got a 1 with?

148
00:06:29,250 --> 00:06:31,082
What type of die, rather?

149
00:06:31,082 --> 00:06:31,665
AUDIENCE: Yes.

150
00:06:31,665 --> 00:06:32,100
PROFESSOR 2: Yeah?

151
00:06:32,100 --> 00:06:33,810
Now what do you
think is more likely?

152
00:06:33,810 --> 00:06:34,817
4-sided or 20-sided?

153
00:06:34,817 --> 00:06:36,400
AUDIENCE: How many
20-sided are there?

154
00:06:36,400 --> 00:06:38,441
PROFESSOR 2: I think I
got 20 20-sided die there.

155
00:06:38,441 --> 00:06:45,110

156
00:06:45,110 --> 00:06:49,080
All right, so raise your hand
if you like a 4-sided die.

157
00:06:49,080 --> 00:06:51,850
Raise your hand if you
like the 20-sided die.

158
00:06:51,850 --> 00:06:52,350
Great.

159
00:06:52,350 --> 00:06:55,230
So that reasoning that
you're doing intuitively

160
00:06:55,230 --> 00:06:57,560
is something that we want
to formalize this week

161
00:06:57,560 --> 00:06:59,930
and next week using
Bayes' Theorem

162
00:06:59,930 --> 00:07:02,460
to do these calculations
in a systematic way,

163
00:07:02,460 --> 00:07:06,380
to evaluate hypotheses
based on data.

164
00:07:06,380 --> 00:07:10,230
And these numbers,
for example, how many

165
00:07:10,230 --> 00:07:12,370
die I had of one
type versus another,

166
00:07:12,370 --> 00:07:14,980
we can encode that information
in what's called a prior,

167
00:07:14,980 --> 00:07:16,369
and we'll come to that today.

168
00:07:16,369 --> 00:07:18,410
And you should've seen in
your reading this idea.

169
00:07:18,410 --> 00:07:22,612

170
00:07:22,612 --> 00:07:24,820
PROFESSOR: OK so I'm going
to work through an example

171
00:07:24,820 --> 00:07:25,420
to start with.

172
00:07:25,420 --> 00:07:31,090
We have 3 types of coins:
type A, B, and C. However

173
00:07:31,090 --> 00:07:34,210
it happens, the probability
of getting heads with type A

174
00:07:34,210 --> 00:07:35,040
is 0.5.

175
00:07:35,040 --> 00:07:36,130
That's a fair coin.

176
00:07:36,130 --> 00:07:40,820
The probability of getting
heads with type B is 0.6,

177
00:07:40,820 --> 00:07:44,000
and of type C is 0.9.

178
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:48,210
And here's a box that
contains two of the fair coins

179
00:07:48,210 --> 00:07:49,460
and one of each of the other.

180
00:07:49,460 --> 00:07:54,070
So two of type A, one of
type B, and one of type C.

181
00:07:54,070 --> 00:07:56,490
Suppose I pick one at
random and I get heads.

182
00:07:56,490 --> 00:08:00,160
So this is like John picking a
die at random, and getting a 1.

183
00:08:00,160 --> 00:08:02,900
I get heads.

184
00:08:02,900 --> 00:08:04,900
Here's the question:
before I flipped it,

185
00:08:04,900 --> 00:08:08,930
I have a prior belief
in the probability

186
00:08:08,930 --> 00:08:11,290
that the coin was
of each type based

187
00:08:11,290 --> 00:08:13,610
on the number in my drawer.

188
00:08:13,610 --> 00:08:17,390
After flipping it,
my believe changes.

189
00:08:17,390 --> 00:08:22,180
The probability will change
based on the data I get.

190
00:08:22,180 --> 00:08:23,940
And so a question
you could ask: what

191
00:08:23,940 --> 00:08:27,590
was learned by
flipping the coin?

192
00:08:27,590 --> 00:08:31,150
What we want to teach you to
do to answer these questions,

193
00:08:31,150 --> 00:08:33,270
we have a nice
way of summarizing

194
00:08:33,270 --> 00:08:36,280
all of that once in a table.

195
00:08:36,280 --> 00:08:44,090
So here the notation, we
have this nice scripty H--

196
00:08:44,090 --> 00:08:44,775
that's no good.

197
00:08:44,775 --> 00:08:48,110

198
00:08:48,110 --> 00:08:49,496
H is our hypothesis.

199
00:08:49,496 --> 00:08:52,820

200
00:08:52,820 --> 00:08:58,740
That is, you're of
type A or B or C.

201
00:08:58,740 --> 00:09:06,690
We're going to make a conjecture
on what we think the coin was.

202
00:09:06,690 --> 00:09:11,330
Before we do anything,
we have a prior.

203
00:09:11,330 --> 00:09:13,910
So what's the
probability of-- how

204
00:09:13,910 --> 00:09:17,240
did I label this-- that
the coin was of type A?

205
00:09:17,240 --> 00:09:21,240

206
00:09:21,240 --> 00:09:24,045
Where all you know is I
pulled it out of the drawer.

207
00:09:24,045 --> 00:09:26,385
So what's the probability
it's of type A.

208
00:09:26,385 --> 00:09:28,135
PROFESSOR 2: Let me
go back and remind you

209
00:09:28,135 --> 00:09:31,570
what the drawer looks like.

210
00:09:31,570 --> 00:09:33,850
What is it?

211
00:09:33,850 --> 00:09:35,040
PROFESSOR: 0.5.

212
00:09:35,040 --> 00:09:36,590
0.5, or I'll write it like this.

213
00:09:36,590 --> 00:09:39,390
2 out of 4, which is 0.5.

214
00:09:39,390 --> 00:09:41,240
And what's the
probability-- I'll

215
00:09:41,240 --> 00:09:52,180
shorten this-- for just
type B. Yeah, 1/4 or 0.25.

216
00:09:52,180 --> 00:09:58,940
The probability that we're
of type C is 1/4 or 0.25.

217
00:09:58,940 --> 00:10:01,565
This was one of our
simpler counting problems.

218
00:10:01,565 --> 00:10:04,130

219
00:10:04,130 --> 00:10:06,380
In the table, you can
see that's encoded

220
00:10:06,380 --> 00:10:09,860
in the line in the
column marked prior.

221
00:10:09,860 --> 00:10:13,150
Before we take any data,
this is what we'd say.

222
00:10:13,150 --> 00:10:16,147
This is the sort
of odds we'd give

223
00:10:16,147 --> 00:10:18,440
if we were going to bet on this.

224
00:10:18,440 --> 00:10:19,770
But now we have some data.

225
00:10:19,770 --> 00:10:22,790

226
00:10:22,790 --> 00:10:28,000
So once we have data we
can get the likelihood.

227
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:32,470

228
00:10:32,470 --> 00:10:34,540
The likelihood is
the probability

229
00:10:34,540 --> 00:10:37,556
of seeing the data
given a hypothesis.

230
00:10:37,556 --> 00:10:40,200

231
00:10:40,200 --> 00:10:43,590
I won't write this out, I'll
just point at the slide.

232
00:10:43,590 --> 00:10:46,749
John has a-- you were going
to make your mouse bigger.

233
00:10:46,749 --> 00:10:47,540
PROFESSOR 2: I was.

234
00:10:47,540 --> 00:10:48,123
PROFESSOR: OK.

235
00:10:48,123 --> 00:10:50,790

236
00:10:50,790 --> 00:10:53,890
So the likelihood column,
we use this term when

237
00:10:53,890 --> 00:10:56,210
we are talking about
maximum likelihood,

238
00:10:56,210 --> 00:11:00,240
is the probability of the
data given the hypothesis.

239
00:11:00,240 --> 00:11:06,010
And this is typically easy,
or often easy, to figure out.

240
00:11:06,010 --> 00:11:07,800
What's the probability
of seeing heads?

241
00:11:07,800 --> 00:11:12,850
Our data was I flipped a heads
if my coin is a 0.5 probability

242
00:11:12,850 --> 00:11:13,350
coin.

243
00:11:13,350 --> 00:11:17,560

244
00:11:17,560 --> 00:11:25,550
So the probability of seeing
heads given a type A coin

245
00:11:25,550 --> 00:11:26,170
is what?

246
00:11:26,170 --> 00:11:28,660
Somebody.

247
00:11:28,660 --> 00:11:30,644
It's 0.5.

248
00:11:30,644 --> 00:11:32,310
This is particularly
easy because that's

249
00:11:32,310 --> 00:11:33,018
what we told you.

250
00:11:33,018 --> 00:11:38,480
The probability of heads
with a type A coin is 0.5.

251
00:11:38,480 --> 00:11:47,160
What about for B
and C. 0.6 and 0.9.

252
00:11:47,160 --> 00:11:52,650
So there right here is the
likelihood column in the table.

253
00:11:52,650 --> 00:11:56,350
Now, how do we
get the posterior?

254
00:11:56,350 --> 00:12:02,390
Bayes' Theorem says
the probability of H

255
00:12:02,390 --> 00:12:04,760
given D, which is what I want.

256
00:12:04,760 --> 00:12:06,630
I want to know,
given this data, what

257
00:12:06,630 --> 00:12:08,670
do I believe the coin to be?

258
00:12:08,670 --> 00:12:11,060
