week, these continuous updating

1031
00:44:00,441 --> 00:44:00,940
problems.

1032
00:44:00,940 --> 00:44:02,110
OK.

1033
00:44:02,110 --> 00:44:03,590
And then, when I
get out of bed, I

1034
00:44:03,590 --> 00:44:06,940
see that the window is
covered in condensation.

1035
00:44:06,940 --> 00:44:08,310
That's some data.

1036
00:44:08,310 --> 00:44:09,440
I can update my beliefs.

1037
00:44:09,440 --> 00:44:12,790
Probably means
it's kind of cold.

1038
00:44:12,790 --> 00:44:13,910
Great.

1039
00:44:13,910 --> 00:44:16,640
Then I can open the
window to let the cat out,

1040
00:44:16,640 --> 00:44:18,870
and a burst of freezing
cold air comes in,

1041
00:44:18,870 --> 00:44:21,328
like it did this morning--
well, actually not this morning.

1042
00:44:21,328 --> 00:44:22,960
This morning was great.

1043
00:44:22,960 --> 00:44:25,700
Yesterday it was cold.

1044
00:44:25,700 --> 00:44:28,841
And again, now I have more
data and I update my beliefs.

1045
00:44:28,841 --> 00:44:29,340
All right.

1046
00:44:29,340 --> 00:44:30,715
You can go through
life this way.

1047
00:44:30,715 --> 00:44:32,810
It'll give you a headache,
but you can do it.

1048
00:44:32,810 --> 00:44:36,070
Now with clinical trials,
the same thing can happen.

1049
00:44:36,070 --> 00:44:37,320
Maybe you do a pilot study.

1050
00:44:37,320 --> 00:44:41,970
Maybe you have some
belief that eating almonds

1051
00:44:41,970 --> 00:44:48,220
causes something,
stomach cramps.

1052
00:44:48,220 --> 00:44:48,970
Great.

1053
00:44:48,970 --> 00:44:50,940
And maybe it's just for you.

1054
00:44:50,940 --> 00:44:52,582
But you want to do
a study about that.

1055
00:44:52,582 --> 00:44:55,040
So maybe you know for yourself
that eating almonds give you

1056
00:44:55,040 --> 00:44:56,500
stomach cramps.

1057
00:44:56,500 --> 00:44:58,550
You're at the Harvard
School of Public Health

1058
00:44:58,550 --> 00:45:00,820
and you really want to
investigate this further,

1059
00:45:00,820 --> 00:45:03,130
so you gather a few
willing subjects,

1060
00:45:03,130 --> 00:45:04,740
you feed them some
almonds, you see

1061
00:45:04,740 --> 00:45:07,080
if they get stomach
cramps, how many of them.

1062
00:45:07,080 --> 00:45:09,800
And maybe your prior
ahead was you just kind of

1063
00:45:09,800 --> 00:45:12,024
felt like you had this
really strong belief that

1064
00:45:12,024 --> 00:45:13,690
almonds cause stomach
cramps, because it

1065
00:45:13,690 --> 00:45:14,670
does for you and you
really haven't even

1066
00:45:14,670 --> 00:45:15,650
asked a lot of other people.

1067
00:45:15,650 --> 00:45:17,483
So you might have a lot
of prior probability

1068
00:45:17,483 --> 00:45:19,630
on that hypothesis being true.

1069
00:45:19,630 --> 00:45:21,060
Once you collect
a few more people

1070
00:45:21,060 --> 00:45:22,930
and maybe you ask your
friends, maybe you

1071
00:45:22,930 --> 00:45:25,054
find that most of them
don't have the same problem.

1072
00:45:25,054 --> 00:45:27,920
Suddenly your posterior
belief changes

1073
00:45:27,920 --> 00:45:30,880
and now you're not quite so
convinced that it's true.

1074
00:45:30,880 --> 00:45:32,470
And then, if you're
really ambitious

1075
00:45:32,470 --> 00:45:35,010
and you have a lot of
grant money from the NIH,

1076
00:45:35,010 --> 00:45:36,880
you recruit 1,000
people and you do

1077
00:45:36,880 --> 00:45:39,020
a randomized controlled
trial with placebo

1078
00:45:39,020 --> 00:45:43,760
and you find out that
exactly 10% of the folks

1079
00:45:43,760 --> 00:45:46,310
complain about the stomach
cramps with almonds.

1080
00:45:46,310 --> 00:45:48,069
Maybe 10% on placebo
also, so you're

1081
00:45:48,069 --> 00:45:49,360
not quite sure what's going on.

1082
00:45:49,360 --> 00:45:51,528
But the point is,
you're getting data

1083
00:45:51,528 --> 00:45:52,736
a little more, a little more.

1084
00:45:52,736 --> 00:45:57,410
And you can keep incorporating
it, updating your beliefs.

1085
00:45:57,410 --> 00:45:58,810
So that's the principal.

1086
00:45:58,810 --> 00:46:00,660
One last thing
I'll point out is,

1087
00:46:00,660 --> 00:46:02,640
what if you have a
prior belief that

1088
00:46:02,640 --> 00:46:07,210
is so strong, so you are
so sure, for example,

1089
00:46:07,210 --> 00:46:10,025
that almonds don't
cause stomach pain,

1090
00:46:10,025 --> 00:46:12,400
because it doesn't for you
and you're just sure that that

1091
00:46:12,400 --> 00:46:14,136
would be ridiculous, right?

1092
00:46:14,136 --> 00:46:15,885
So you've put your
prior probability at 0.

1093
00:46:15,885 --> 00:46:18,564

1094
00:46:18,564 --> 00:46:20,230
How much evidence
will it take, how much

1095
00:46:20,230 --> 00:46:22,680
data will take for
you to be convinced?

1096
00:46:22,680 --> 00:46:25,280

1097
00:46:25,280 --> 00:46:26,150
Infinite.

1098
00:46:26,150 --> 00:46:30,480
No amount of data it's going
to convince you otherwise.

1099
00:46:30,480 --> 00:46:33,580
This is why whenever you do
this kind of Bayesian Updating,

1100
00:46:33,580 --> 00:46:37,620
it's generally best to leave
a little bit of possibility

1101
00:46:37,620 --> 00:46:39,580
for Santa Claus, OK.

1102
00:46:39,580 --> 00:46:41,300
Like a little bit.

1103
00:46:41,300 --> 00:46:46,040
Just so that should a fat white
man come down your chimney

1104
00:46:46,040 --> 00:46:48,170
and deliver the
presents one year,

1105
00:46:48,170 --> 00:46:52,300
you have a
possibility to adjust.

1106
00:46:52,300 --> 00:46:55,340
So those are some
things to keep in mind.

1107
00:46:55,340 --> 00:46:57,770
I think we've got one
more board question

1108
00:46:57,770 --> 00:46:59,860
that Jerry's going to lead.

1109
00:46:59,860 --> 00:47:05,080
PROFESSOR: Right so it's
nice to get probabilities

1110
00:47:05,080 --> 00:47:08,110
for hypotheses, but one
thing you also want to do

1111
00:47:08,110 --> 00:47:10,850
is predict what's
going to come next.

1112
00:47:10,850 --> 00:47:15,320
And so that's what we call
probabilistic prediction.

1113
00:47:15,320 --> 00:47:19,870
If I pick one of the John's 5
die, and I'm about to roll it,

1114
00:47:19,870 --> 00:47:23,200
you could tell me using the
Law of Total Probability

1115
00:47:23,200 --> 00:47:27,740
the probability that I get a 5.

1116
00:47:27,740 --> 00:47:30,530
And we've done that, we
did that in the first unit

1117
00:47:30,530 --> 00:47:32,890
on probability in this class.

1118
00:47:32,890 --> 00:47:37,960
But suppose he rolls a 5 first.

1119
00:47:37,960 --> 00:47:41,650
Now I can update my
probabilities for which

1120
00:47:41,650 --> 00:47:43,200
die it is, which
is going to update

1121
00:47:43,200 --> 00:47:48,200
my estimation of the
probability of rolling, say a 4

1122
00:47:48,200 --> 00:47:49,779
on the next roll.

1123
00:47:49,779 --> 00:47:51,820
This is what we'll call
probabilistic prediction.

1124
00:47:51,820 --> 00:47:54,240
We can predict what's
going to happen next,

1125
00:47:54,240 --> 00:47:59,104
at least with probabilities,
based on the data

1126
00:47:59,104 --> 00:47:59,770
that we've seen.

1127
00:47:59,770 --> 00:48:03,660
We update our predictions
based on that.

1128
00:48:03,660 --> 00:48:05,220
So here's a set up.

1129
00:48:05,220 --> 00:48:06,510
D1 is the first roll.

1130
00:48:06,510 --> 00:48:07,380
D2 is the second.

1131
00:48:07,380 --> 00:48:10,840

1132
00:48:10,840 --> 00:48:12,202
I'll do this example.

1133
00:48:12,202 --> 00:48:13,410
Oh no, this a board question.

1134
00:48:13,410 --> 00:48:15,280
You're going to do this.

1135
00:48:15,280 --> 00:48:16,430
You're on your own here.

1136
00:48:16,430 --> 00:48:18,860
So first, you
don't know anything

1137
00:48:18,860 --> 00:48:23,510
about the die except that 1
of the 5 was chosen at random.

1138
00:48:23,510 --> 00:48:27,320
What's the probability that
the first roll will be a 5?

1139
00:48:27,320 --> 00:48:31,690
Now you've rolled that once,
and you're going to roll again.

1140
00:48:31,690 --> 00:48:34,030
And you can ask, well
now I've seen some data.

1141
00:48:34,030 --> 00:48:38,350
I have some information
about which die was chosen.

1142
00:48:38,350 --> 00:48:41,810
What's the probability that
I'll see a 4 on the next die.

1143
00:48:41,810 --> 00:48:45,280
So that's your job to find
that for this problem.

1144
00:48:45,280 --> 00:48:52,493

1145
00:48:52,493 --> 00:48:54,826
PROFESSOR 2: Cool, alright
so this is your first answer?

1146
00:48:54,826 --> 00:48:55,492
AUDIENCE: Right.

1147
00:48:55,492 --> 00:48:58,810
And then, now we're
just multiplying across.

1148
00:48:58,810 --> 00:48:59,806
You get 0.

1149
00:48:59,806 --> 00:49:03,292

1150
00:49:03,292 --> 00:49:14,248
1/180, 1/320,
1/740, [INAUDIBLE].

1151
00:49:14,248 --> 00:49:19,726
And then add those up.

1152
00:49:19,726 --> 00:49:22,150
PROFESSOR 2: Yeah, get
out your calculator.

1153
00:49:22,150 --> 00:49:23,775
What are you dividing
by to normalize?

1154
00:49:23,775 --> 00:49:25,397
AUDIENCE: Is this--
I don't know.

1155
00:49:25,397 --> 00:49:26,480
PROFESSOR 2: That's right.

1156
00:49:26,480 --> 00:49:31,190
So this is, when you add these
up, exactly the probability

1157
00:49:31,190 --> 00:49:32,290
of the 5, right?

1158
00:49:32,290 --> 00:49:34,040
So now if you want to
repeat this process,

1159
00:49:34,040 --> 00:49:36,920
you need to use your
normalized posterior instead

1160
00:49:36,920 --> 00:49:37,920
of the original prior.

1161
00:49:37,920 --> 00:49:38,826
AUDIENCE: That's what we were--

1162
00:49:38,826 --> 00:49:39,732
PROFESSOR 2: Yeah.

1163
00:49:39,732 --> 00:49:41,550
Great.

1164
00:49:41,550 --> 00:49:43,100
Now, you just need
to do division.

1165
00:49:43,100 --> 00:49:46,140
That I can't help you with.

1166
00:49:46,140 --> 00:49:48,780
Calculator.

1167
00:49:48,780 --> 00:49:50,226
Division skills, either way.

1168
00:49:50,226 --> 00:49:58,207

1169
00:49:58,207 --> 00:49:59,040
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

1170
00:49:59,040 --> 00:50:13,764

1171
00:50:13,764 --> 00:50:15,555
AUDIENCE: Now this is
the probability of 4,

1172
00:50:15,555 --> 00:50:17,642
or the probability
of 4 getting 5?

1173
00:50:17,642 --> 00:50:18,725
PROFESSOR 2: That's right.

1174
00:50:18,725 --> 00:50:21,350

1175
00:50:21,350 --> 00:50:25,700
So tell me what you
did to get these.

1176
00:50:25,700 --> 00:50:28,676
AUDIENCE: So this
column [INAUDIBLE]

1177
00:50:28,676 --> 00:50:32,148
which we calculated for,
and then you sum it up

1178
00:50:32,148 --> 00:50:34,628
to get the total
probability of getting a 5.

1179
00:50:34,628 --> 00:50:36,116
And then [INAUDIBLE]
normalized it,

1180
00:50:36,116 --> 00:50:40,100
and then took the new
[INAUDIBLE] times the same--

1181
00:50:40,100 --> 00:50:41,475
PROFESSOR 2: The
same likelihood.

1182
00:50:41,475 --> 00:50:43,183
AUDIENCE: And then
you get the new column

1183
00:50:43,183 --> 00:50:44,265
and then you add it up.

1184
00:50:44,265 --> 00:50:46,425
[INAUDIBLE]

1185
00:50:46,425 --> 00:50:47,300
PROFESSOR 2: Perfect.

1186
00:50:47,300 --> 00:50:49,832
Now you said, just for the
heck of it you normalized it,

1187
00:50:49,832 --> 00:50:52,040
but it's actually really
important that you normalize

1188
00:50:52,040 --> 00:50:54,539
it, because if you're going to
use the Law of Total Probably

1189
00:50:54,539 --> 00:50:57,580
again, right, you've got to be
working with a probability mass

1190
00:50:57,580 --> 00:50:59,362
function, something
that adds to 1 here.

1191
00:50:59,362 --> 00:51:01,320
If you didn't normalize,
then your final answer

1192
00:51:01,320 --> 00:51:03,300
would get multiplied
by something, right?

1193
00:51:03,300 --> 00:51:05,220
Whatever that
normalization constant was,

1194
00:51:05,220 --> 00:51:05,710
or its reciprocal.

1195
00:51:05,710 --> 00:51:06,210
Perfect.

1196
00:51:06,210 --> 00:51:12,955

1197
00:51:12,955 --> 00:51:13,830
Check these guys out.

1198
00:51:13,830 --> 00:51:20,110

1199
00:51:20,110 --> 00:51:23,617
PROFESSOR: And this right
here is not a probability,

1200
00:51:23,617 --> 00:51:24,700
because it's unnormalized.

1201
00:51:24,700 --> 00:51:26,670
So what should you
normalize this by?

1202
00:51:26,670 --> 00:51:29,230
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

1203
00:51:29,230 --> 00:51:29,920
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

1204
00:51:29,920 --> 00:51:32,410
In other words, if you made a
normalized probability here,

1205
00:51:32,410 --> 00:51:34,810
it would be this divided by
that, this divided by that.

1206
00:51:34,810 --> 00:51:36,010
AUDIENCE: So all we need
to do is divide this--

1207
00:51:36,010 --> 00:51:37,051
PROFESSOR: Exactly right.

1208
00:51:37,051 --> 00:51:54,042

1209
00:51:54,042 --> 00:51:55,208
PROFESSOR 2: How's it going?

1210
00:51:55,208 --> 00:51:57,580
AUDIENCE: It's going fine.

1211
00:51:57,580 --> 00:51:58,587
So we're just saying--

1212
00:51:58,587 --> 00:51:59,420
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

1213
00:51:59,420 --> 00:52:17,379

1214
00:52:17,379 --> 00:52:19,170
PROFESSOR 2: So, what
did you get for this?

1215
00:52:19,170 --> 00:52:20,490
How did you find it?

1216
00:52:20,490 --> 00:52:23,480
So you summed up this, right?

1217
00:52:23,480 --> 00:52:26,189
Great, and then what
did you do next?

1218
00:52:26,189 --> 00:52:27,730
AUDIENCE: We do the
same thing for 4.

1219
00:52:27,730 --> 00:52:29,354
PROFESSOR 2: So,
starting from scratch.

1220
00:52:29,354 --> 00:52:31,940
AUDIENCE: Yeah, starting
from scratch if you roll a 4.

1221
00:52:31,940 --> 00:52:32,800
AUDIENCE: OK.

1222
00:52:32,800 --> 00:52:36,780
So how does that
incorporated the fact

1223
00:52:36,780 --> 00:52:38,840
that you first rolled a 5?

1224
00:52:38,840 --> 00:52:41,478
AUDIENCE: So we're trying to
go back to the original Bayes,

1225
00:52:41,478 --> 00:52:43,310
but that didn't work
out so well because we

1226
00:52:43,310 --> 00:52:44,960
don't know how to
calculate this.

1227
00:52:44,960 --> 00:52:46,293
PROFESSOR 2: Exactly, all right.

1228
00:52:46,293 --> 00:52:47,990
So this is no easier than that.

1229
00:52:47,990 --> 00:52:54,230
So here's the idea: so you
start with this belief, right?

1230
00:52:54,230 --> 00:52:55,660
And you have your likelihood.

1231
00:52:55,660 --> 00:52:57,493
You multiply them, Law
of Total Probability,

1232
00:52:57,493 --> 00:52:59,850
and you get the
probability of rolling a 5.

1233
00:52:59,850 --> 00:53:03,070
Now at that point, after
you've rolled this 5,

1234
00:53:03,070 --> 00:53:05,070
your beliefs have
changed based on that

1235
00:53:05,070 --> 00:53:08,370
about the probability that
you have each of the 5 dice.

1236
00:53:08,370 --> 00:53:12,500
So if we take that and
you use that as your prior

1237
00:53:12,500 --> 00:53:16,320
here, then the likelihood,
multiply and sum,

1238
00:53:16,320 --> 00:53:18,304
that should give you--

1239
00:53:18,304 --> 00:53:19,220
AUDIENCE: I like that.

1240
00:53:19,220 --> 00:53:20,130
PROFESSOR 2: OK?

1241
00:53:20,130 --> 00:53:21,857
AUDIENCE: Oh, but
now we have decimals.

1242
00:53:21,857 --> 00:53:23,190
AUDIENCE: Now you have decimals.

1243
00:53:23,190 --> 00:53:24,555
I can't make your life too easy.

1244
00:53:24,555 --> 00:53:31,093

1245
00:53:31,093 --> 00:53:31,926
AUDIENCE: Use these.

1246
00:53:31,926 --> 00:53:35,430

1247
00:53:35,430 --> 00:53:38,010
PROFESSOR: Right, so
you multiply this number

1248
00:53:38,010 --> 00:53:39,984
by this, this number by this.

1249
00:53:39,984 --> 00:53:41,900
So in the end, you'll
get all of these numbers

1250
00:53:41,900 --> 00:53:44,440
except they're all
multiplied by, divided by.

1251
00:53:44,440 --> 00:53:48,540
So you should divide this
by-- to get a probability.

1252
00:53:48,540 --> 00:53:50,940
That make sense?

1253
00:53:50,940 --> 00:53:55,670
So you have to be careful for
figuring out probabilities

1254
00:53:55,670 --> 00:53:59,760
of hypotheses, we can avoid
using the unnormalized.

1255
00:53:59,760 --> 00:54:01,450
We don't have to
keep normalizing.

1256
00:54:01,450 --> 00:54:03,890
But when you want to do
posterior prediction,

1257
00:54:03,890 --> 00:54:07,280
you want real
probabilities of data.

1258
00:54:07,280 --> 00:54:09,280
So you're going to
have to normalize

1259
00:54:09,280 --> 00:54:11,700
these numbers at some point.

1260
00:54:11,700 --> 00:54:13,384
Either first or at the end.

1261
00:54:13,384 --> 00:54:15,300
It's probably, if you're
going to do it a lot,

1262
00:54:15,300 --> 00:54:16,345
easier to just keep doing it.

1263
00:54:16,345 --> 00:54:17,220
AUDIENCE: OK, Thanks.

1264
00:54:17,220 --> 00:54:30,700

1265
00:54:30,700 --> 00:54:32,182
AUDIENCE: How are we doing?

1266
00:54:32,182 --> 00:54:33,140
PROFESSOR: You tell me.

1267
00:54:33,140 --> 00:54:36,090

1268
00:54:36,090 --> 00:54:37,520
It's a beautiful use of color.

1269
00:54:37,520 --> 00:54:40,339

1270
00:54:40,339 --> 00:54:41,172
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

1271
00:54:41,172 --> 00:54:48,735

1272
00:54:48,735 --> 00:54:50,860
PROFESSOR: So is this
normalized or not normalized?

1273
00:54:50,860 --> 00:54:51,980
AUDIENCE: This is normalized.

1274
00:54:51,980 --> 00:54:52,896
PROFESSOR: Normalized.

1275
00:54:52,896 --> 00:54:54,960
Good, because you are
real probabilities there.

1276
00:54:54,960 --> 00:54:55,670
Yes, thank you.

